Class Query<T>

java.lang.Object
io.github.jdbctemplatemapper.core.Query<T>
All Implemented Interfaces:
IQueryExecute<T>, IQueryFluent<T>, IQueryHasMany<T>, IQueryHasOne<T>, IQueryJoinColumnManySide<T>, IQueryJoinColumnTypeSide<T>, IQueryLimitOffsetClause<T>, IQueryOrderBy<T>, IQueryPopulateProperty<T>, IQueryThroughJoinColumns<T>, IQueryThroughJoinTable<T>, IQueryType<T>, IQueryWhere<T>
public class Query<T> extends Object implements IQueryFluent<T>
Fluent style queries for relationships hasOne, hasMany, hasMany through (many to many). 
 See Querying
 relationships for more info

      public IQueryJoinColumnTypeSide<T> joinColumnTypeSide(String joinColumnTypeSide)
      Join column for hasOne relationship: The join column (the foreign key) is on the table of the type model. Example: Order hasOne Customer. The join column(foreign key) will be on the table order (of the type model). The join column should not have a table prefix.

    • where

      public IQueryWhere<T> where(String whereClause, Object... params)
      The SQL where clause. When querying relationships the where clause can include columns from both type and related tables. The parameters can be positional or named parameters. 
       Examples:
 1) where("orders.status = ? and orders.customer_id = ?", "COMPLETE", 1)
 2) where("orders.status = :status and orders.customer_id = :customerId", 
       new MapSqlParameterSource().addValue("status", "COMPLETE").addValue("customerId", 1))
      Specified by:
      where in interface IQueryPopulateProperty<T>
      Specified by:
      where in interface IQueryType<T>
      Parameters:
      whereClause - the whereClause.
      params - varArgs for the whereClause.
      Returns:
      interface with the next methods in the chain
